## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort-related APIs that all throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8:

| API Found | Location | Pattern |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Cleanup on forced termination |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Keep thread alive after abort |

The key paradigm shift: .NET Framework *forcibly injected* `ThreadAbortException` into your thread. .NET 8 requires **cooperative cancellation** — your code must *voluntarily* check a `CancellationToken` and respond.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls wake up promptly on cancel.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // Exit the loop (replaces Thread.ResetAbort + finally flow)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // Signal cooperative cancellation (replaces Thread.Abort)

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No abort to reset — just exit the loop after cleanup |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then abort | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | `Join` blocks until the thread exits *or* the timeout expires — no busy-sleep |

---

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **`GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** If it blocks on I/O or a queue without checking `token`, cancellation stalls until it unblocks on its own. Example fix:

   ```csharp
   // Before — blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
   private Item GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

   // After — wakes immediately when token is cancelled
   private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
   ```

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` mid-chain.** Only catch it at the top-level loop. If `ProcessItem` calls sub-methods, let the exception propagate up.

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds timer/callback resources. The `Stop()` method above disposes it. Leaking it causes resource leaks.

4. **Cancellation is not instant.** It only fires at the next checkpoint (`token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`) or cancellation-aware API call. Add checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` if it does long-running work:

   ```csharp
   private void ProcessItem(Item item, CancellationToken token)
   {
       StepOne(item);
       token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
       StepTwo(item);
       token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
       StepThree(item);
   }
   ```

5. **Replace `Thread.Sleep` inside the loop** (if any) with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so the thread wakes on cancellation instead of sleeping the full duration.
